something that publishers and booksellers help to create. These popular texts become part of mass culture, where they are connected to public events. The genre of memoir, and even genre itself, ceases to be an empty classification category and becomes part of social action and consumer culture at the same time. From James Frey’s controversial A Million Little Pieces to memoirs about bartending, Iran, the liberation of Dachau, computer hacking, and the impact of 9/11, this book argues that the memoir boom is more than a publishing trend. It is becoming the way American readers try to understand major events in terms of individual experiences. The memoir boom is one of the ways that citizenship as a category of belonging between private and public spheres is now articulated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aAutobiography. 0aPublishers and publishingxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aPublishers and publishingzUnited States. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aCultural Studies. 4aLanguage Arts & Disciplines: Publishing. 4aLife Writing. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican literature.  aAutobiography.  aMemoir boom.  aPopular Culture.  aTheory.  abook publishers.  abook publishing.  aliterary market.  aprint on demand.  apublishing business.  apublishing history.  apublishing industry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554589401423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554589401/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles